<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1016,1259]" pageId="22" pageNumber="125">
This species has simple, slim, not elongated hindlegs without tufted or roughened scales. The abdomen is slender, spindle shaped, clearly separated from thorax. The transparent areas of the wings are superficially similar to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[258,392,1160,1186]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Tipulamima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[258,392,1160,1186]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="125">Tipulamima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the wings are distinctly narrower, the anal area of the hindwing much smaller. Barcoding place this species within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duckworth &amp; Eichlin" authorityYear="1977" box="[425,537,1196,1222]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Osminiini">Osminiini</taxonomicName>
(Pühringer personal communication, unpublished) we here provisionally transfer it to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1919" box="[203,342,1232,1258]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Pyranthrene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[203,342,1232,1258]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="125">Pyranthrene</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
